I have tested this modified code and it works when run with Eclipse on Windows with OpenJDK, Java Version 17.

There were several problems with your code which meant the logic didn&#39;t make any sense.

In particular, using a recursive method to get user input which you can&#39;t short circuit escape from, makes no sense at all.

Doing things like `inputStream.nextint()` is also a sign of some fragile logic. It is usually better to read a whole line into a string (something that can&#39;t really fail) and then process the string to get the input you want.

In this case you want to:

- Strip any whitespace and newlines
- Perform integer conversion with `Integer.valueOf`

Doing it this way will be much more reliable.

I have no idea what `nextInt` does, or under what conditions it works. (eg: does it work if you prepend tabs or spaces? does it work with extra characters following the string? etc...)

There are so many possible combinations of input - the behaviour could be any number of possibilities and only reading the documentation carefully would resolve this.

By the way, the actual reason for your failure (assides from logic errors) was because `nextInt` reads just that - the integer - without the new line character. A new line is left in your input stream, which is then picked up by the next input reading function call.

```
package test;

import java.util.InputMismatchException;
import java.util.Scanner;

public class App {
	
    private static int getPressure(Scanner l, String pres) {

        String ans;
        boolean badUserInput = true;
        Integer num = Integer.valueOf(0);
        
        //get user input only if it is an integer, otherwise return error message
        //and get user input again
        while(badUserInput) {
            try {
                System.out.println(&quot;Please input &quot; + pres + &quot; Blood Pressure:&quot;);
                ans = l.nextLine();
                ans = ans.strip();
                num = Integer.valueOf(ans);
                badUserInput = false;
            } catch (InputMismatchException e) {
                System.out.println(&quot;Sorry, that didn&#39;t work. Please ensure your input is a whole number.&quot;);
            }
        }
        
        return num.intValue();
    }

    private static boolean checkPressure(Scanner l, int num, String pres) {
        System.out.println(&quot;You typed &quot; + num + &quot;, is that correct? (Yes/No)&quot;);

        //if input does not match one of expected values (&quot;Yes&quot; and &quot;No&quot;)
        //return error message and take input again
        String ans;
        boolean badUserInput = true;
        boolean returnOk = false;
        while(badUserInput ) {
            ans = l.nextLine();
            
            if (ans.equals(&quot;Yes&quot;)) {
                badUserInput = false;
                returnOk = true;
            } else if (ans.equals(&quot;No&quot;)) {
            	badUserInput = false;
            	returnOk = false;
            } else {
                System.out.println(&quot;Sorry, invalid input, please type &#39;Yes&#39; or &#39;No&#39;&quot;);
            }
        }
        
        return returnOk;
    }
    
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        int sys = 0;
        int dias = 0;
        String systolic = &quot;Systolic&quot;;
        String diastolic = &quot;Diastolic&quot;;
        Scanner p = new Scanner(System.in);
        
        boolean repeat = true;
        while(repeat) {
        	sys = getPressure(p, systolic);
        	boolean returnedValue = checkPressure(p, sys, systolic);
        	repeat = !returnedValue;
        }
        
        repeat = true;
        while(repeat) {
        	dias = getPressure(p, diastolic);
        	boolean returnedValue = checkPressure(p, sys, diastolic);
        	repeat = !returnedValue;
        }
    }
}
```

