It runs seven times because the moment you set `activoHilo3` to false is to late to stop the seventh pass through the loop.

Lets start the description at the moment where the loop is running the sixth time: `Thread.sleep(5000)` finishes and `contador1` is 5.

The next action in your thread is to call `runOnUiThread(...)`. This call schedules the `Runnable` to run some time later and returns immediately. After that the code in your thread checks the condition of the `while` loop and finds `activoHilo3` to be still `true`, so it starts a seventh time into the while loop.

Then, some time later, the code in the `Runnable` is executed on the UI thread. This code triggers the display of the toast, checks the value of `contador1` and sets `activoHilo3` to `false`. But at this moment your thread is already in the seventh loop, executing the `Thread.sleep(5000)`.

---
To fix the problem I would move the loop condition out of the `Runnable` into the `while` loop:

    class Hilo3 extends Thread {
        @Override
        public void run() {
            while (activoHilo3) {
                try {
                    Thread.sleep(5000);
                    runOnUiThread(new Runnable() {
                        @Override
                        public void run() {
                            Toast.makeText(Prueba.this, &quot;Hilo3&quot;, Toast.LENGTH_SHORT).show();
                        }
                    });
                } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                    e.printStackTrace();
                }
                if (contador1 == 5) {
                    activoHilo3 = false;
                }
                contador1++;
            }
        }
    }

Or, since extending `Thread` is rarely the right choice:

