You can configure Jackson&#39;s `ObjectMapper` to return a null object when deserializing a JSON response that does not match the POJO class. 

Here is some code:

    ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();
    mapper.findAndRegisterModules();
    mapper.disable(DeserializationFeature.FAIL_ON_UNKNOWN_PROPERTIES);
    mapper.disable(DeserializationFeature.ADJUST_DATES_TO_CONTEXT_TIME_ZONE);
    mapper.disable(SerializationFeature.WRITE_DATES_AS_TIMESTAMPS);
    mapper.disable(SerializationFeature.WRITE_DATES_WITH_CONTEXT_TIME_ZONE);
    
    String responseBody = response.body().string();
    POJO pojo = null;
    
    try {
        pojo = mapper.readValue(responseBody, POJO.class);
    } catch (JsonProcessingException e) {
        // Handle exception if needed
    }
    
   
    if (pojo == null) {
        pojo = new POJO();
    }

This way, if the JSON response does not contain properties that match the POJO class, the resulting POJO object will have all its properties set to null, as per your requirement.

You need to read POJO response only and only when valid response status received - normally `HTTP/1.1 200 Ok`. In other cases - read it as a error response:
```
@Getter
